Title   : Rs 14 crore to Rs 390 crore! Facebook's early investor strikes gold again, this time with Urban Company IPO 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-17T06:18:45
Fetched : 2025-09-17T12:07:41.117068
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/rs-14-crore-to-rs-390-crore-facebooks-early-investor-strikes-gold-again-this-time-with-urban-company-ipo/articleshow/123937117.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Accel first backed the home services startup over a decade ago, buying shares at an average price of Rs 3.77 apiece. At the IPO price band of Rs 103, the same slice of shares it picked up for Rs 14.3 crore is now worth Rs 390 crore — a return multiple of nearly 27 times.
And this is just part of the story. Accel had invested a total of Rs 55 crore in Urban Company, giving it 14.56 crore shares. At current IPO valuations, the firm’s stake is just over Rs 1,500 crore. Even after cashing out a chunk worth Rs 390 crore, it will still be sitting on shares valued at over Rs 1,100 crore.
The windfall adds to Accel’s track record of high-profile exits. The firm has been an early backer of the social media platform Facebook, owned by Meta. The company’s investment turned into an 800-fold return by the time the social media giant went public in 2012. In India, the Urban Company exit strengthens its portfolio of homegrown winners, where it has also backed companies such as Acko and Cult.fit, which are both unlisted.
Abhinav Chaturvedi, Partner at Accel, “We at Accel have been fortunate to partner with Urban Company since Day 0, and today’s IPO is both a moment of pride and immense excitement. While the public listing is a financial milestone for this one-of-its-kind company, for us at Accel the true win is the societal impact UC has created, giving thousands of partners dignity and autonomy of work while helping them upskill for the future. This listing is also another proof point that India’s startup ecosystem is coming of age, with public markets embracing digitally native businesses. For Urban Company, this is only the beginning, the best is yet to come.”
The initial public offering (IPO) of Urban Company drew strong interest across the three days, with the issue being subscribed 103.6 times. The bulk of the bids came from qualified institutional buyers (QIBs) and non-institutional investors.
Urban Company’s IPO comprised a fresh issue of Rs 472 crore and an offer for sale worth Rs 1,428 crore, with investors including Bessemer India Capital, Elevation Capital and Tiger Global also trimming stakes.
The company recently turned profitable as it reported a net profit of Rs 240 crore in FY25, against a loss of Rs 93 crore a year ago, while revenue grew 36% to Rs 1,261 crore.
While near-term valuations appear stretched, experts say Urban Company’s leadership in a largely unorganised Rs 6,000 crore home services market and its ability to scale new categories offer significant structural growth potential.
“Urban Company, formerly known as UrbanClap, is a leading tech-enabled home services platform offering a wide range of services, including beauty and wellness, appliance repair, cleaning, and maintenance. In FY25, Urban Company reported Revenue of Rs 1,144 crore (38% YoY growth) and Rs 240 crore (a significant turnaround from a Rs 93 crore loss in FY24). For those who received allotment, consider booking partial profit and hold the rest for long-term gains with a stop loss of Rs 120,” Shivani Nyati, Head of Wealth at Swastika Investmart Ltd, said.
Also read: How should investors respond to Urban Co.’s stock debut?
At about 11:24 AM, Urban Company shares were trading at Rs 168.46 on the NSE, higher by 64% over the upper IPO price band of Rs 103.
