Net Profit (TTM/latest) (2025-09-17): 24.11B INR

Title   : Dev Accelerator shares surge to upper circuit after flat listing at ₹61 
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-17T05:21:37
Fetched : 2025-09-17T12:09:15.455373
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/stock-markets/dev-accelerator-shares-surge-to-upper-circuit-after-flat-listing-at-61/article70059841.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Shares of Dev Accelerator made a flat debut on the stock exchanges, listing at par with its IPO price of ₹61. On the National Stock Exchange (NSE), the stock opened at ₹61, while on the BSE, it inched up 0.5 per cent to ₹61.30.
Post-listing, the stock gained momentum, hitting the upper circuit on both bourses at ₹64.15 on the BSE and ₹64 on the NSE.
Shivani Nyati, Head of Wealth at Swastika Investmart Ltd, emphasised that the company’s modest profit margins and high debt levels warrant caution. Risky investors can hold for medium to long term with stop loss of ₹50.
₹143.35-cr IPO sees 63.97x subscription
The IPO, which was closely watched in the market, indicateed a healthy demand for emerging companies in the capital markets. The 143.35-crore IPO received 63.97 times subscription on the final day of bidding.
Retail investors garnered 164.72 times subscription. The category for non-institutional investors (NIIs) received 87.97 times subscription, while the qualified institutional buyers (QIBs) quota got subscribed 20.30 times.
The IPO, promoted by Dev Information Technology Ltd., was entirely a fresh issue of 2.35 crore equity shares worth ₹143.35 crore at a price band of ₹56-61 per share.
The company secured ₹63 crore from anchor investors.
It proposed that the proceeds from the issue will be used for fit-outs in new centres and their security deposits, debt repayment and general corporate purposes such as strategic initiatives, marketing, brand building, and lease liability payments.
More Like This
Published on September 17, 2025

Title   : Dev Accelerator shares jump 5% after flat debut at IPO price. Should you buy, sell, or hold? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-17T05:55:34
Fetched : 2025-09-17T12:09:15.455373
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/dev-accelerator-shares-jump-5-after-flat-debut-at-ipo-price-should-you-buy-sell-or-hold/articleshow/123936681.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Rs 143-crore IPO, priced in the Rs 56-61 band, attracted healthy investor interest during the subscription process. However, the grey market premium (GMP) remained subdued ahead of the listing, with shares trading at a modest 3% premium.
What should investors do?
Valuations appear rich, with the stock trading at a P/E of 310x, making it one of the 16 costliest stocks in the country. Sunny Agrawal of SBI Securities has taken a ‘Neutral’ stance on the issue, recommending that investors track the company’s performance post-listing before taking fresh positions, and caution against any FOMO-driven approach.
SBI Securities prefers to monitor execution and profitability improvements before adopting a more positive view.
“While strong subscription numbers indicate investor confidence, the company’s modest profit margins and high debt levels warrant caution. Risk-tolerant investors can hold for the medium to long term with a stop loss of Rs 50 per share,” said Shivani Nyati, Head of Wealth at Swastika Investmart.
She added, “The company aims to capitalize on growing demand for flexible office spaces, catering to startups, SMEs, and large enterprises seeking scalable solutions.”
Anand Rathi recommends a long-term holding strategy, highlighting that the company has expanded its offerings to include HR, IT, and software services through Saasjoy, enhancing client retention and meeting evolving workplace and technology needs.
Additionally, through its associate Scaleax Advisory, it helps GCCs build global teams in India by providing facility and payroll management, as well as recruitment solutions such as talent sourcing, AI-based screening, and team augmentation.
“The sector remains highly competitive and fragmented, and the issue appears aggressively priced based on current valuations, requiring careful consideration of market dynamics and execution capabilities in an evolving flexible workspace landscape,” said Nitant Darekar, Research Analyst at Bonanza.
He added, “Dev has positioned itself as one of the larger flex space operators in tier-2 markets, offering managed office solutions with lease tenures of 5-9 years and coworking spaces. The company has demonstrated an operational turnaround since FY24, with improving financials and expansion plans including three new centers via LOIs, notably its first international venture in Sydney, Australia.”
Financials
The company has shown strong revenue momentum, with topline growth from Rs 70 crore in FY23 to Rs 159 crore in FY25, registering a CAGR of over 50%. EBITDA margins remain healthy at above 50%, though bottom-line profitability is modest, with PAT at Rs 2 crore in FY25. High lease liabilities and interest costs continue to weigh on net earnings. Post-IPO, the company’s debt-to-equity ratio is expected to ease from 2.4x to about 1x, aided by IPO proceeds earmarked for debt repayment and fit-outs at proposed centers.
(Disclaimer: Recommendations, suggestions, views, and opinions given by the experts are their own. These do not represent the views of The Economic Times)
