Title   : Mukesh Ambani planning Reliance Retail IPO: 5 things investors should watch out for 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-17T05:43:27
Fetched : 2025-09-17T13:20:54.715129
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/mukesh-ambani-planning-reliance-retail-ipo-5-things-investors-should-watch-out-for/slideshow/123936599.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Mukesh Ambani is reportedly planning a blockbuster IPO for Reliance Retail in 2027, a year after the planned listing of Reliance Jio. The retail arm of Reliance Industries could be valued at nearly $200 billion at the time of its listing. This highly anticipated IPO is expected to be one of the largest in India's history, attracting global investor attention. Here are 5 things investors should watch out for
ANI
2/6
A look at the financials
Reliance Retail has shown strong financial growth, with profit increasing by 28.3% year-on-year to Rs 3,271 crore in Q1 FY26. Revenue also grew by 11% to Rs 84,171 crore in the same period.
IANS
3/6
Strong growth
The company is ranked among the fastest-growing retailers in the world and is the only Indian retailer in Deloitte's Global Top 100.
iStock
4/6
Strategic moves for a stronger IPO
In preparation for the IPO, Reliance Retail has been streamlining its operations, including shutting down underperforming stores to improve profit margins. The company has also demerged its fast-moving consumer goods (FMCG) unit, Reliance Consumer Products, to be a direct subsidiary of the parent company.
ETMarkets.com
5/6
Bumper exits
The IPO is expected to provide an exit for a number of marquee global investors who had invested in the company earlier. Some of these investors include Singapore’s GIC, Abu Dhabi Investment Authority (ADIA), Qatar Investment Authority, KKR, TPG, and Silver Lake.
ETMarkets.com
6/6
The retail king of India
Reliance Retail is India's largest retailer, with the widest reach and the biggest store footprint. It operates nearly 20,000 stores across different formats and has over 349 million registered customers. The company is also ranked among the top five global retailers by store count and in the top 30 by revenue.

